---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const rawBase = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const base = rawBase.endsWith('/') ? rawBase : rawBase + '/';
---

<Layout title="Lecture" description="Nursing lecture on acid-base physiology: fixed vs volatile acids, compensation, clinical causes, and interactive quizzes.">
  <div class="lecture-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Page Header -->
      <div class="page-header">
        <h1>Acid-Base Physiology: Nursing Lecture</h1>
        <p class="page-subtitle">
          A guided lecture covering the physiology of acids and bases, how the lungs and kidneys maintain pH,
          compensation mechanisms, clinical causes, and practice quizzes.
        </p>
        <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
          <strong>Jump to:</strong>
          <a href="#acid-types">Acid Types</a>
          <a href="#lungs-vs-kidneys">Lungs vs Kidneys</a>
          <a href="#compensation">Compensation</a>
          <a href="#clinical-causes">Clinical Causes</a>
          <a href="#cns-depression">CNS Depression</a>
          <a href="#scenarios">Scenarios</a>
          <a href="#quiz">Quiz</a>
        </nav>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
           SECTION 1 — VOLATILE VS FIXED ACIDS (AND BASES)
      ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="lec-section" id="acid-types">
        <h2><span class="section-num">1</span> Volatile Acids, Fixed Acids, and Their Counterparts</h2>

        <p class="lead">
          Not all acids are created equal. In human physiology, acids are divided into two fundamental
          categories based on one key question: <strong>can this acid be converted to a gas and exhaled?</strong>
          The answer determines which organ system eliminates it.
        </p>

        <div class="two-col-cards">
          <!-- Volatile Acid -->
          <div class="type-card volatile-acid">
            <div class="type-header">
              <span class="type-badge volatile">Volatile</span>
              <h3>Volatile Acid — CO₂</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              A <strong>volatile acid</strong> is one that can be converted into a gas and eliminated by the lungs.
              Carbon dioxide (CO₂) is the only clinically significant volatile acid in human physiology.
            </p>
            <div class="equation-box">
              CO₂ + H₂O &nbsp;⇌&nbsp; H₂CO₃ &nbsp;⇌&nbsp; H⁺ + HCO₃⁻
              <div class="eq-caption">CO₂ dissolves into carbonic acid, then dissociates into hydrogen ions and bicarbonate.</div>
            </div>
            <ul class="type-list">
              <li>Produced continuously by cellular metabolism (≈ 15,000–20,000 mmol/day)</li>
              <li>Carried in blood as dissolved CO₂, bicarbonate, and carbaminohemoglobin</li>
              <li>Eliminated entirely by the <strong>lungs</strong> through ventilation</li>
              <li>Regulated <em>within minutes</em> — fast response system</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="key-point">
              <strong>💨 Key:</strong> When ventilation increases (hyperventilation), more CO₂ is blown off →
              fewer H⁺ ions → pH rises. When ventilation decreases (hypoventilation), CO₂ accumulates →
              more H⁺ ions → pH falls.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Fixed Acids -->
          <div class="type-card fixed-acid">
            <div class="type-header">
              <span class="type-badge fixed">Fixed</span>
              <h3>Fixed (Non-Volatile) Acids</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              <strong>Fixed acids</strong> — also called non-volatile acids — cannot be converted to a gas.
              They have no respiratory route of elimination and must be excreted by the <strong>kidneys</strong>.
            </p>
            <ul class="type-list">
              <li><strong>Lactic acid</strong> — from anaerobic metabolism (shock, intense exercise)</li>
              <li><strong>Ketoacids</strong> — acetoacetic acid &amp; beta-hydroxybutyric acid (DKA, starvation)</li>
              <li><strong>Phosphoric acid</strong> — from phosphoprotein/phospholipid metabolism</li>
              <li><strong>Sulfuric acid</strong> — from sulfur-containing amino acid metabolism</li>
              <li><strong>Ingested acids</strong> — aspirin (salicylic acid), methanol metabolites, ethylene glycol</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="key-point warning">
              <strong>⚠️ Critical:</strong> The lungs <em>cannot</em> eliminate fixed acids. Breathing faster
              can lower CO₂ and temporarily raise pH, but it does not remove lactic acid, ketoacids, or
              ingested toxins — that is exclusively the kidneys' job (hours to days).
            </div>
            <div class="produced-day">
              Fixed acid load: ≈ <strong>50–100 mEq/day</strong> from normal metabolism
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Counterparts: Volatile Base removal & Fixed Bases -->
        <h3 class="subsection-title">The Counterparts — How Bases Fit In</h3>
        <p>
          Just as acids are divided into volatile and fixed, we can think about how the body handles the
          <em>base side</em> of the equation.
        </p>

        <div class="two-col-cards">
          <!-- Volatile "base" — CO₂ removal -->
          <div class="type-card volatile-base">
            <div class="type-header">
              <span class="type-badge volatile">Volatile</span>
              <h3>Volatile Base Effect — Blowing Off CO₂</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              There is no true volatile base gas in human physiology, but the respiratory system creates
              an equivalent <em>alkalinizing effect</em> by eliminating CO₂.
            </p>
            <ul class="type-list">
              <li>Exhaling CO₂ drives the carbonic-acid equilibrium <strong>left</strong>: H⁺ + HCO₃⁻ → H₂CO₃ → CO₂ ↑ + H₂O</li>
              <li>Net result: hydrogen ions are consumed → pH <strong>rises</strong></li>
              <li>This is <em>physiologically equivalent</em> to adding a base — but it works only on the CO₂ side</li>
              <li>Hyperventilation exploits this: anxiety, pain, fever, mechanical over-ventilation</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="key-point">
              <strong>💡 Analogy:</strong> Think of the lungs as a "volatile acid dump" — when they dump more
              CO₂, pH rises. When they dump less, pH falls.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Fixed Base — Bicarbonate -->
          <div class="type-card fixed-base">
            <div class="type-header">
              <span class="type-badge fixed">Fixed</span>
              <h3>Fixed Base — Bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻)</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              Bicarbonate is the primary <strong>fixed base</strong> of the body. Unlike CO₂, it cannot be
              exhaled; it is manufactured, retained, or excreted exclusively by the <strong>kidneys</strong>.
            </p>
            <ul class="type-list">
              <li>Normal range: <strong>22–26 mEq/L</strong></li>
              <li>Kidneys reabsorb HCO₃⁻ (proximal tubule) or generate new HCO₃⁻ (distal tubule) to combat acidosis</li>
              <li>Kidneys excrete HCO₃⁻ (reduce reabsorption) to combat alkalosis</li>
              <li>Renal compensation takes <strong>hours to days</strong> — much slower than lung response</li>
              <li>Also includes phosphate buffers and ammonia in urine as additional fixed-base mechanisms</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="key-point">
              <strong>🔑 Memory hook:</strong> <em>Bicarbonate = Kidneys.</em>
              If you see HCO₃⁻ out of range, the kidneys are either the cause of the problem
              or are actively compensating for it.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Summary comparison table -->
        <div class="comparison-table-wrap">
          <h3 class="subsection-title">Side-by-Side Comparison</h3>
          <table class="lec-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Feature</th>
                <th class="col-va">Volatile Acid (CO₂)</th>
                <th class="col-fa">Fixed Acids</th>
                <th class="col-vb">Volatile "Base" Effect</th>
                <th class="col-fb">Fixed Base (HCO₃⁻)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Can be exhaled?</td>
                <td class="col-va">✅ Yes</td>
                <td class="col-fa">❌ No</td>
                <td class="col-vb">✅ (CO₂ removal)</td>
                <td class="col-fb">❌ No</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Regulating organ</td>
                <td class="col-va">Lungs</td>
                <td class="col-fa">Kidneys</td>
                <td class="col-vb">Lungs</td>
                <td class="col-fb">Kidneys</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Response speed</td>
                <td class="col-va">Minutes</td>
                <td class="col-fa">Hours – days</td>
                <td class="col-vb">Minutes</td>
                <td class="col-fb">Hours – days</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>ABG parameter</td>
                <td class="col-va">PaCO₂</td>
                <td class="col-fa">(causes ↓ HCO₃⁻)</td>
                <td class="col-vb">PaCO₂ ↓</td>
                <td class="col-fb">HCO₃⁻</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Examples</td>
                <td class="col-va">CO₂ from metabolism</td>
                <td class="col-fa">Lactate, ketoacids, aspirin, phosphate, sulfate</td>
                <td class="col-vb">Hyperventilation</td>
                <td class="col-fb">Renal HCO₃⁻ retention/excretion</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>If increased → causes</td>
                <td class="col-va">Respiratory acidosis</td>
                <td class="col-fa">Metabolic acidosis</td>
                <td class="col-vb">Respiratory alkalosis</td>
                <td class="col-fb">Metabolic alkalosis</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
           SECTION 2 — LUNGS VS KIDNEYS
      ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="lec-section" id="lungs-vs-kidneys">
        <h2><span class="section-num">2</span> What the Lungs Can and Cannot Do</h2>

        <div class="organ-compare">
          <div class="organ-card lung-card">
            <div class="organ-icon">🫁</div>
            <h3>The Lungs</h3>
            <p class="organ-subtitle">Respiratory Regulation — Fast but Limited</p>

            <div class="can-do">
              <h4>✅ CAN Do</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Increase or decrease ventilation within <strong>seconds to minutes</strong></li>
                <li>Raise pH by blowing off CO₂ (hyperventilate)</li>
                <li>Lower pH by retaining CO₂ (hypoventilate)</li>
                <li>Compensate for metabolic acidosis by hyperventilating (Kussmaul breathing)</li>
                <li>Compensate for metabolic alkalosis by hypoventilating (mildly, limited)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="cannot-do">
              <h4>❌ CANNOT Do</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Eliminate lactic acid — must wait for kidneys &amp; liver</li>
                <li>Clear ketoacids (DKA) — only kidneys can excrete them</li>
                <li>Excrete ingested toxins or drug metabolites (aspirin, methanol, ethylene glycol)</li>
                <li>Restore bicarbonate — that requires renal tubular reabsorption</li>
                <li>Achieve full compensation on their own — pH correction always remains partial via lungs alone</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="organ-abg">
              <strong>ABG marker:</strong> <span class="badge-co2">PaCO₂ (35–45 mmHg)</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="organ-card kidney-card">
            <div class="organ-icon">🫘</div>
            <h3>The Kidneys</h3>
            <p class="organ-subtitle">Metabolic Regulation — Slower but Powerful</p>

            <div class="can-do">
              <h4>✅ CAN Do</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Reabsorb bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) from the filtrate to combat acidosis</li>
                <li>Generate <em>new</em> bicarbonate via hydrogen ion secretion</li>
                <li>Excrete fixed acids as ammonium (NH₄⁺) and titratable acids</li>
                <li>Excrete excess bicarbonate to combat alkalosis</li>
                <li>Provide near-complete compensation over hours to days</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="cannot-do">
              <h4>❌ CANNOT Do</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Respond quickly — renal compensation takes <strong>hours to days</strong></li>
                <li>Help in acute respiratory emergencies (no time)</li>
                <li>Eliminate CO₂ — that is strictly the lungs' job</li>
                <li>Function normally if damaged (renal failure → metabolic acidosis)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="organ-abg">
              <strong>ABG marker:</strong> <span class="badge-hco3">HCO₃⁻ (22–26 mEq/L)</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <strong>🧠 Clinical Pearl:</strong> In DKA, the patient breathes rapidly (Kussmaul respirations)
          to blow off CO₂ and temporarily raise pH. But this does <em>not</em> remove ketoacids —
          it only compensates for them. Treatment (insulin, IV fluids) is needed to stop ketoacid
          production and allow the kidneys to excrete the fixed acid load.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
           SECTION 3 — COMPENSATION
      ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="lec-section" id="compensation">
        <h2><span class="section-num">3</span> Compensation — Partial vs Full</h2>

        <p class="lead">
          When one system (respiratory or metabolic) develops a primary disorder, the <em>opposite</em>
          system responds to restore pH toward normal. This is <strong>compensation</strong>. It is
          always a corrective response — never the cause of the primary problem.
        </p>

        <div class="comp-stages">
          <div class="comp-stage uncompensated">
            <div class="comp-stage-label">Stage 1</div>
            <h3>Uncompensated</h3>
            <p>Only one component is abnormal. The compensating system has not yet responded (acute onset) or is unable to.</p>
            <div class="comp-example">
              <strong>Example — Respiratory Acidosis, Uncompensated:</strong><br/>
              pH 7.28 ↓ &nbsp;|&nbsp; PaCO₂ 58 ↑ &nbsp;|&nbsp; HCO₃⁻ 24 (normal)
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="comp-stage partial">
            <div class="comp-stage-label">Stage 2</div>
            <h3>Partially Compensated</h3>
            <p>Both components are abnormal. The compensating system is working but pH is still outside the normal range (7.35–7.45).</p>
            <div class="comp-example">
              <strong>Example — Respiratory Acidosis, Partially Compensated:</strong><br/>
              pH 7.31 ↓ &nbsp;|&nbsp; PaCO₂ 58 ↑ &nbsp;|&nbsp; HCO₃⁻ 30 ↑ (kidneys retaining HCO₃⁻)
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="comp-stage full">
            <div class="comp-stage-label">Stage 3</div>
            <h3>Fully Compensated</h3>
            <p>Both components are abnormal but pH has been pulled back into the normal range. The underlying disorder still exists.</p>
            <div class="comp-example">
              <strong>Example — Respiratory Acidosis, Fully Compensated:</strong><br/>
              pH 7.38 (normal) &nbsp;|&nbsp; PaCO₂ 58 ↑ &nbsp;|&nbsp; HCO₃⁻ 34 ↑
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-rules">
          <h3>Compensation Rules at a Glance</h3>
          <table class="lec-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Primary Disorder</th>
                <th>Primary Change</th>
                <th>Compensatory Response</th>
                <th>Compensating Organ</th>
                <th>Speed</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Respiratory Acidosis</td>
                <td>CO₂ ↑ → pH ↓</td>
                <td>HCO₃⁻ ↑ (kidneys retain)</td>
                <td>Kidneys</td>
                <td>Hours – days</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Respiratory Alkalosis</td>
                <td>CO₂ ↓ → pH ↑</td>
                <td>HCO₃⁻ ↓ (kidneys excrete)</td>
                <td>Kidneys</td>
                <td>Hours – days</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Metabolic Acidosis</td>
                <td>HCO₃⁻ ↓ → pH ↓</td>
                <td>CO₂ ↓ (hyperventilation)</td>
                <td>Lungs</td>
                <td>Minutes</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Metabolic Alkalosis</td>
                <td>HCO₃⁻ ↑ → pH ↑</td>
                <td>CO₂ ↑ (hypoventilation)</td>
                <td>Lungs</td>
                <td>Minutes – hours</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-warning">
          <strong>⚠️ Important:</strong> Full compensation does <strong>not</strong> mean the patient is cured.
          Both values remain abnormal. You must identify the primary disorder by asking:
          "Which value changes in the same direction as the pH?" — that component caused the disorder.
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <strong>🔑 Quick Rule:</strong> The body compensates but <em>never overcorrects</em>.
          If pH has normalized, look at whether it leans toward acidosis (&lt;7.40) or alkalosis (&gt;7.40)
          to identify the primary side.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
           SECTION 4 — CLINICAL CAUSES
      ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="lec-section" id="clinical-causes">
        <h2><span class="section-num">4</span> Clinical Causes — Vomiting, Diarrhea, Hyperventilation, Hypoventilation, and Substances</h2>

        <div class="cause-grid">

          <!-- Vomiting -->
          <div class="cause-card alkalosis-cause">
            <div class="cause-header">
              <span class="cause-emoji">🤢</span>
              <div>
                <h3>Vomiting / NG Suctioning</h3>
                <span class="disorder-tag tag-met-alk">→ Metabolic Alkalosis</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Gastric juice is rich in hydrochloric acid (HCl). When HCl is lost through vomiting or
              nasogastric suctioning, the body loses H⁺ ions without losing HCO₃⁻ — the ratio tips toward alkalosis.
            </p>
            <div class="mechanism-box">
              <strong>Mechanism:</strong> HCl loss → fewer H⁺ in blood → pH rises → HCO₃⁻ rises
            </div>
            <ul class="cause-list">
              <li>Prolonged vomiting (pyloric stenosis, hyperemesis gravidarum, eating disorders)</li>
              <li>Nasogastric tube suctioning post-surgery</li>
              <li>Associated hypokalemia worsens alkalosis (K⁺ shifts out of cells, H⁺ shifts in)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="abg-example">
              pH ↑ &nbsp;|&nbsp; PaCO₂ normal–↑* &nbsp;|&nbsp; HCO₃⁻ ↑
              <span class="abg-note">*lungs hypoventilate slightly to compensate</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Diarrhea -->
          <div class="cause-card acidosis-cause">
            <div class="cause-header">
              <span class="cause-emoji">💧</span>
              <div>
                <h3>Diarrhea</h3>
                <span class="disorder-tag tag-met-acid">→ Metabolic Acidosis</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Intestinal and pancreatic secretions below the stomach are rich in bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻).
              Diarrhea causes large losses of HCO₃⁻, leaving excess H⁺ unchecked.
            </p>
            <div class="mechanism-box">
              <strong>Mechanism:</strong> HCO₃⁻ lost in stool → less base to buffer H⁺ → pH falls
            </div>
            <ul class="cause-list">
              <li>Acute infectious diarrhea (cholera, C. diff, viral gastroenteritis)</li>
              <li>Inflammatory bowel disease flares</li>
              <li>Ileostomy or colostomy with high output</li>
              <li>Laxative abuse</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="abg-example">
              pH ↓ &nbsp;|&nbsp; PaCO₂ normal–↓* &nbsp;|&nbsp; HCO₃⁻ ↓
              <span class="abg-note">*lungs hyperventilate to compensate</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Hyperventilation -->
          <div class="cause-card alkalosis-cause">
            <div class="cause-header">
              <span class="cause-emoji">😤</span>
              <div>
                <h3>Hyperventilation</h3>
                <span class="disorder-tag tag-resp-alk">→ Respiratory Alkalosis</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Breathing too fast or too deeply blows off excess CO₂ faster than it is produced.
              Less CO₂ means fewer H⁺ ions → pH rises.
            </p>
            <div class="mechanism-box">
              <strong>Mechanism:</strong> ↑ Ventilation → CO₂ ↓ → H⁺ ↓ → pH ↑
            </div>
            <ul class="cause-list">
              <li>Anxiety, panic attacks (most common cause)</li>
              <li>Pain or fever</li>
              <li>Pregnancy (progesterone stimulates breathing)</li>
              <li>High altitude (hypoxia drives ventilation)</li>
              <li>Sepsis (early — fever &amp; inflammatory mediators)</li>
              <li>Over-ventilation on a mechanical ventilator</li>
              <li>Salicylate (aspirin) overdose — direct stimulation of respiratory center</li>
              <li>Pulmonary embolism or pulmonary edema (hypoxia triggers hyperventilation)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="abg-example">
              pH ↑ &nbsp;|&nbsp; PaCO₂ ↓ &nbsp;|&nbsp; HCO₃⁻ normal–↓*
              <span class="abg-note">*kidneys excrete HCO₃⁻ to compensate (slow)</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Hypoventilation -->
          <div class="cause-card acidosis-cause">
            <div class="cause-header">
              <span class="cause-emoji">😴</span>
              <div>
                <h3>Hypoventilation</h3>
                <span class="disorder-tag tag-resp-acid">→ Respiratory Acidosis</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Breathing too slowly or too shallowly allows CO₂ to accumulate in the blood.
              More CO₂ → more H⁺ → pH falls.
            </p>
            <div class="mechanism-box">
              <strong>Mechanism:</strong> ↓ Ventilation → CO₂ ↑ → H⁺ ↑ → pH ↓
            </div>
            <ul class="cause-list">
              <li><strong>Opioid overdose</strong> — CNS depression suppresses respiratory drive</li>
              <li><strong>Sedative/benzodiazepine overdose</strong></li>
              <li>COPD with CO₂ retention ("CO₂ retainer")</li>
              <li>Obstructive sleep apnea</li>
              <li>Neuromuscular disease (ALS, Guillain-Barré, myasthenia gravis)</li>
              <li>Chest wall injury (flail chest, severe pain limiting breathing)</li>
              <li>Stroke or brainstem injury affecting respiratory center</li>
              <li>Obesity hypoventilation syndrome (Pickwickian syndrome)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="abg-example">
              pH ↓ &nbsp;|&nbsp; PaCO₂ ↑ &nbsp;|&nbsp; HCO₃⁻ normal–↑*
              <span class="abg-note">*kidneys retain HCO₃⁻ to compensate (slow)</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Substances Table -->
        <h3 class="subsection-title" id="substances">Ingested / Administered Substances</h3>
        <p>Many drugs and toxins directly disturb acid-base balance. Knowing these is high-yield for NCLEX and clinical practice.</p>

        <div class="substance-tables">
          <div class="substance-table-wrap">
            <h4 class="sub-table-title acidosis-title">Substances Causing Acidosis</h4>
            <table class="lec-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Substance</th>
                  <th>Type</th>
                  <th>Mechanism</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Opioids</strong> (morphine, heroin, fentanyl)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-resp-acid">Respiratory</span></td>
                  <td>CNS depression → hypoventilation → CO₂ ↑</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Benzodiazepines</strong> (diazepam, lorazepam)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-resp-acid">Respiratory</span></td>
                  <td>CNS/respiratory depression → CO₂ ↑</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Barbiturates</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="tag-resp-acid">Respiratory</span></td>
                  <td>CNS depression → hypoventilation → CO₂ ↑</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Aspirin (salicylates)</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-acid">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Direct fixed acid load (salicylic acid); also causes early respiratory alkalosis</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Methanol</strong> (wood alcohol)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-acid">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Metabolized to formic acid → high anion gap metabolic acidosis</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Ethylene glycol</strong> (antifreeze)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-acid">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Metabolized to oxalic acid → high anion gap metabolic acidosis</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Metformin</strong> (in renal failure)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-acid">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Lactic acidosis due to mitochondrial inhibition</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Ammonium chloride</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-acid">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Direct H⁺ donor → metabolic acidosis (rarely used clinically)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Alcohol (chronic)</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-acid">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Ketoacidosis + lactic acidosis from impaired hepatic metabolism</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <div class="substance-table-wrap">
            <h4 class="sub-table-title alkalosis-title">Substances Causing Alkalosis</h4>
            <table class="lec-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Substance</th>
                  <th>Type</th>
                  <th>Mechanism</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Antacids</strong> (sodium bicarbonate, calcium carbonate)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-alk">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Direct HCO₃⁻ load → metabolic alkalosis ("milk-alkali syndrome")</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Loop diuretics</strong> (furosemide, bumetanide)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-alk">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Chloride &amp; K⁺ loss → contraction alkalosis + HCO₃⁻ retention</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Thiazide diuretics</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-alk">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Similar to loop diuretics — volume contraction + H⁺ loss</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Corticosteroids</strong> (high dose)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-met-alk">Metabolic</span></td>
                  <td>Mineralocorticoid effect: Na⁺ retention, H⁺ &amp; K⁺ excretion</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Aspirin (salicylates — early)</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="tag-resp-alk">Respiratory</span></td>
                  <td>Direct stimulation of medullary respiratory center → hyperventilation</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Progesterone</strong> (pregnancy, medroxyprogesterone)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-resp-alk">Respiratory</span></td>
                  <td>Stimulates respiratory center → chronic mild hyperventilation</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Nicotine / Caffeine</strong> (mild)</td>
                  <td><span class="tag-resp-alk">Respiratory</span></td>
                  <td>CNS stimulation → slight increase in ventilation</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
           SECTION 5 — CNS DEPRESSION IN ACIDOSIS
      ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="lec-section" id="cns-depression">
        <h2><span class="section-num">5</span> CNS Depression in Acidosis</h2>

        <p class="lead">
          Acidosis — especially severe metabolic acidosis — has profound effects on the central nervous
          system (CNS). Understanding these effects helps you recognize a critically ill patient before
          the ABG result even comes back.
        </p>

        <div class="cns-grid">
          <div class="cns-card">
            <h3>🧠 Why Does Acidosis Depress the CNS?</h3>
            <p>
              Low pH disrupts neuronal membrane excitability and impairs neurotransmitter function.
              H⁺ ions cross the blood-brain barrier and directly inhibit neuronal firing.
              CO₂ crosses even more readily (lipid-soluble), making respiratory acidosis especially
              potent in causing cerebral depression.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>H⁺ and CO₂ diffuse into cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), lowering CSF pH</li>
              <li>Reduced neuronal excitability → drowsiness, confusion, coma</li>
              <li>Impaired cardiac conduction → arrhythmias, hypotension</li>
              <li>Vasodilation of cerebral vessels → ↑ intracranial pressure (from CO₂)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="cns-card">
            <h3>📉 Clinical Progression of Acidosis</h3>
            <div class="progression-steps">
              <div class="prog-step">
                <div class="prog-badge mild">Mild (pH 7.20–7.35)</div>
                <p>Headache, restlessness, mild confusion, fatigue</p>
              </div>
              <div class="prog-step">
                <div class="prog-badge moderate">Moderate (pH 7.10–7.20)</div>
                <p>Lethargy, disorientation, nausea, deep Kussmaul breathing (metabolic)</p>
              </div>
              <div class="prog-step">
                <div class="prog-badge severe">Severe (pH &lt; 7.10)</div>
                <p>Stupor, coma, cardiac arrhythmias, hemodynamic instability</p>
              </div>
              <div class="prog-step">
                <div class="prog-badge critical">Critical (pH &lt; 6.80)</div>
                <p>Death — protein denaturation, irreversible cellular damage</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cns-specifics">
          <h3>Respiratory Acidosis vs Metabolic Acidosis — CNS Differences</h3>
          <div class="two-col-compare">
            <div class="compare-item">
              <h4>Respiratory Acidosis</h4>
              <p>CO₂ is lipid-soluble and crosses the blood-brain barrier rapidly. Even moderate hypercapnia
              (CO₂ 60–80 mmHg) causes significant CNS depression: somnolence, confusion, "CO₂ narcosis."
              This is particularly relevant in COPD patients on supplemental oxygen — removing hypoxic drive
              can cause further hypoventilation and worsening CO₂ retention.</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>CO₂ narcosis:</strong> CO₂ &gt; 70–80 mmHg → stupor, coma</li>
                <li>Flapping tremor (asterixis) is a classic sign</li>
                <li>Papilledema from cerebral vasodilation can occur in severe hypercapnia</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-item">
              <h4>Metabolic Acidosis</h4>
              <p>H⁺ and organic acids (lactate, ketoacids) cause slower but progressive CNS dysfunction.
              The body compensates by increasing ventilation (Kussmaul breathing) which can partially
              protect the brain, but severe metabolic acidosis is still life-threatening.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Kussmaul respirations: deep, rapid breathing — a compensatory sign</li>
                <li>DKA: fruity breath from acetone (volatile ketone)</li>
                <li>Uremic encephalopathy in renal failure — from accumulated toxins + acidosis</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-warning">
          <strong>⚠️ Nursing Priority:</strong> A patient with worsening acidosis (pH &lt; 7.20) who becomes increasingly
          somnolent or confused is at risk for respiratory arrest — the CNS depression may blunt their
          drive to breathe, creating a vicious cycle. <strong>Notify the provider immediately for any pH &lt; 7.25,
          or at any pH if consciousness is declining. Airway management is the priority.</strong>
          Prepare for potential intubation if the patient cannot protect their airway.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
           SECTION 6 — CLINICAL SCENARIOS
      ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="lec-section" id="scenarios">
        <h2><span class="section-num">6</span> Clinical Scenarios</h2>
        <p class="lead">Apply your knowledge to these real-world cases. Click "Reveal Analysis" to see the interpretation.</p>

        <div class="scenario-list">

          <div class="scenario-card">
            <div class="scenario-header">
              <span class="scenario-num">Case 1</span>
              <h3>The Diabetic Patient with Deep Breathing</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="scenario-body">
              <p><strong>History:</strong> 22-year-old with Type 1 Diabetes presents with 3 days of polyuria,
              polydipsia, nausea, and vomiting. You notice she is breathing deeply and rapidly.</p>
              <div class="abg-values">
                <span>pH: <strong>7.22</strong></span>
                <span>PaCO₂: <strong>18</strong> mmHg</span>
                <span>HCO₃⁻: <strong>7</strong> mEq/L</span>
              </div>
              <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="s1-answer">Reveal Analysis</button>
              <div class="scenario-answer" aria-hidden="true" id="s1-answer">
                <p><strong>Disorder:</strong> Metabolic Acidosis, Partially Compensated</p>
                <p><strong>Primary problem:</strong> HCO₃⁻ critically low (7) → pH ↓. Caused by ketoacid accumulation (DKA) — these are <em>fixed acids</em> that the lungs cannot eliminate.</p>
                <p><strong>Compensation:</strong> PaCO₂ 18 (↓) — she is hyperventilating (Kussmaul breathing) to blow off CO₂ and raise pH. The lungs are doing the only thing they can: reducing the volatile acid component. But they cannot touch the ketoacid load.</p>
                <p><strong>Lung limitation:</strong> Despite heroic respiratory compensation, pH is still 7.22 because fixed ketoacids remain. Only insulin + fluids (stopping ketogenesis) and kidney excretion of ketoacids will resolve the metabolic acidosis.</p>
                <p><strong>Action:</strong> IV insulin, IV fluids, electrolyte monitoring. Airway monitoring — if she tires out, she will stop compensating and crash rapidly.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="scenario-card">
            <div class="scenario-header">
              <span class="scenario-num">Case 2</span>
              <h3>Post-Op Patient with Altered Mental Status</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="scenario-body">
              <p><strong>History:</strong> 68-year-old post-abdominal surgery, received IV morphine PCA.
              Nurse finds patient extremely somnolent, RR 6, SpO₂ 88%.</p>
              <div class="abg-values">
                <span>pH: <strong>7.18</strong></span>
                <span>PaCO₂: <strong>72</strong> mmHg</span>
                <span>HCO₃⁻: <strong>26</strong> mEq/L</span>
              </div>
              <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="s2-answer">Reveal Analysis</button>
              <div class="scenario-answer" aria-hidden="true" id="s2-answer">
                <p><strong>Disorder:</strong> Respiratory Acidosis, Uncompensated (Acute)</p>
                <p><strong>Primary problem:</strong> CO₂ 72 (↑↑) → pH critically low. Opioid-induced CNS depression has suppressed the respiratory drive. CO₂ is a volatile acid retained because the lungs aren't ventilating adequately.</p>
                <p><strong>Why uncompensated?</strong> HCO₃⁻ is still 26 (normal) — the kidneys haven't had time to respond (this is acute, minutes to hours).</p>
                <p><strong>CNS depression:</strong> CO₂ narcosis — CO₂ 72 has crossed the BBB and is directly suppressing CNS. The somnolence makes hypoventilation worse (vicious cycle).</p>
                <p><strong>Action:</strong> Naloxone (opioid reversal), stimulate breathing, prepare for possible bag-mask ventilation or intubation. Stop PCA.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="scenario-card">
            <div class="scenario-header">
              <span class="scenario-num">Case 3</span>
              <h3>Post-Op Patient with NG Tube</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="scenario-body">
              <p><strong>History:</strong> 55-year-old post-gastrectomy on continuous NG suction for 4 days.
              Complains of muscle cramps and tingling.</p>
              <div class="abg-values">
                <span>pH: <strong>7.52</strong></span>
                <span>PaCO₂: <strong>48</strong> mmHg</span>
                <span>HCO₃⁻: <strong>38</strong> mEq/L</span>
              </div>
              <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="s3-answer">Reveal Analysis</button>
              <div class="scenario-answer" aria-hidden="true" id="s3-answer">
                <p><strong>Disorder:</strong> Metabolic Alkalosis, Partially Compensated</p>
                <p><strong>Primary problem:</strong> HCO₃⁻ 38 (↑↑) → pH ↑. 4 days of NG suctioning removed massive amounts of HCl from the stomach — loss of the fixed acid H⁺ leaves the body relatively alkalotic.</p>
                <p><strong>Compensation:</strong> PaCO₂ 48 (↑) — the lungs are hypoventilating slightly to retain CO₂ (volatile acid) to counterbalance the alkalosis. However, respiratory compensation for alkalosis is limited because hypoventilation risks dangerous hypoxemia.</p>
                <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Muscle cramps/tetany from hypocalcemia — alkalosis causes calcium to bind more to albumin, reducing ionized Ca²⁺.</p>
                <p><strong>Action:</strong> Replace K⁺ and Cl⁻ (NS or KCl). Consider stopping suctioning or switching to intermittent. Monitor calcium.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="scenario-card">
            <div class="scenario-header">
              <span class="scenario-num">Case 4</span>
              <h3>Anxious Patient in the ED</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="scenario-body">
              <p><strong>History:</strong> 24-year-old brought to ED after a panic attack. Breathing rapidly,
              complains of tingling in fingers and toes, lips feel numb.</p>
              <div class="abg-values">
                <span>pH: <strong>7.58</strong></span>
                <span>PaCO₂: <strong>22</strong> mmHg</span>
                <span>HCO₃⁻: <strong>20</strong> mEq/L</span>
              </div>
              <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="s4-answer">Reveal Analysis</button>
              <div class="scenario-answer" aria-hidden="true" id="s4-answer">
                <p><strong>Disorder:</strong> Respiratory Alkalosis, Partially Compensated</p>
                <p><strong>Primary problem:</strong> CO₂ 22 (↓↓) → pH ↑. Anxiety-driven hyperventilation blew off CO₂ far below normal — the only volatile acid is now too low.</p>
                <p><strong>Compensation:</strong> HCO₃⁻ 20 (↓ slightly) — kidneys have started excreting bicarbonate to lower pH. The fact that it's only mildly reduced suggests this is relatively acute.</p>
                <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Perioral and acral tingling — alkalemia increases albumin binding of calcium, reducing free ionized Ca²⁺ (functional hypocalcemia), which raises neuromuscular excitability. This is the same mechanism seen in true hypocalcemia.</p>
                <p><strong>Action:</strong> Reassurance and breathing retraining are first-line. Controlled slow breathing (diaphragmatic, or breathing into cupped hands) helps retain CO₂; paper bags are no longer recommended due to hypoxia risk. Treat the underlying anxiety/panic disorder.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="scenario-card">
            <div class="scenario-header">
              <span class="scenario-num">Case 5</span>
              <h3>COPD Patient on Oxygen</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="scenario-body">
              <p><strong>History:</strong> 72-year-old with severe COPD, lives at home on 1–2 L O₂.
              Admitted for increasing shortness of breath. Alert but dyspneic.</p>
              <div class="abg-values">
                <span>pH: <strong>7.36</strong></span>
                <span>PaCO₂: <strong>62</strong> mmHg</span>
                <span>HCO₃⁻: <strong>34</strong> mEq/L</span>
              </div>
              <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="s5-answer">Reveal Analysis</button>
              <div class="scenario-answer" aria-hidden="true" id="s5-answer">
                <p><strong>Disorder:</strong> Respiratory Acidosis, Fully Compensated (Chronic)</p>
                <p><strong>Primary problem:</strong> CO₂ 62 (↑) from chronic COPD-related hypoventilation.</p>
                <p><strong>Compensation:</strong> HCO₃⁻ 34 (↑↑) — the kidneys have had time (days to weeks) to retain large amounts of bicarbonate, pulling the pH to 7.36 (within normal range, but low-normal indicating the acidotic side).</p>
                <p><strong>Key insight:</strong> This patient's "normal" CO₂ is not 40 — it's 62. Do not aggressively correct CO₂ too fast. This patient relies partly on a hypoxic drive to breathe. High-flow O₂ can remove that drive and worsen CO₂ retention.</p>
                <p><strong>Action:</strong> Controlled O₂ (titrate to SpO₂ 88–92%), bronchodilators, treat exacerbation. Avoid high-dose O₂.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
           SECTION 7 — QUIZ
      ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="lec-section" id="quiz">
        <h2><span class="section-num">7</span> Knowledge Check Quiz</h2>
        <p class="lead">Test your understanding. Select an answer, then reveal the explanation.</p>

        <div class="quiz-list">

          <div class="quiz-item" data-correct="b">
            <p class="quiz-question">1. A patient with DKA has a PaCO₂ of 16 mmHg and pH 7.24. Why can't the lungs fully correct the pH back to normal?</p>
            <div class="quiz-options">
              <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="a"/> The lungs have already compensated fully — this ABG is fully compensated.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="b"/> Ketoacids are <em>fixed acids</em> that the lungs cannot eliminate; only the kidneys can excrete them.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="c"/> The bicarbonate is too high for the lungs to compensate.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="d"/> The lungs can only respond to metabolic alkalosis, not metabolic acidosis.</label>
            </div>
            <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q1-exp">Reveal Explanation</button>
            <div class="quiz-explanation" aria-hidden="true" id="q1-exp">
              <strong>✅ Correct Answer: B</strong><br/>
              Ketoacids (acetoacetic acid, beta-hydroxybutyric acid) are fixed, non-volatile acids. The lungs can only reduce CO₂ (a volatile acid), which temporarily raises pH but cannot remove the underlying ketoacid load. Treatment with insulin stops ketoacid production, and the kidneys excrete what remains.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="quiz-item" data-correct="c">
            <p class="quiz-question">2. A patient has pH 7.50, PaCO₂ 50, HCO₃⁻ 38. What is the primary disorder and what caused the elevated HCO₃⁻?</p>
            <div class="quiz-options">
              <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="a"/> Respiratory alkalosis; the kidneys are excreting acid.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="b"/> Respiratory acidosis; the kidneys are retaining acid.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="c"/> Metabolic alkalosis; HCO₃⁻ rose first (primary), CO₂ ↑ is compensation.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="d"/> Metabolic acidosis; HCO₃⁻ is being used up buffering acid.</label>
            </div>
            <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q2-exp">Reveal Explanation</button>
            <div class="quiz-explanation" aria-hidden="true" id="q2-exp">
              <strong>✅ Correct Answer: C</strong><br/>
              pH is high (alkalosis). HCO₃⁻ is high — matching the pH direction (ROME = Equal for Metabolic). Primary disorder = Metabolic Alkalosis. The lungs compensate by retaining CO₂ (hypoventilation), which is why PaCO₂ is elevated. Common cause: prolonged vomiting or NG suctioning.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="quiz-item" data-correct="a">
            <p class="quiz-question">3. Which of the following is a <em>volatile</em> acid?</p>
            <div class="quiz-options">
              <label><input type="radio" name="q3" value="a"/> Carbonic acid (H₂CO₃) derived from CO₂</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q3" value="b"/> Lactic acid</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q3" value="c"/> Phosphoric acid</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q3" value="d"/> Beta-hydroxybutyric acid</label>
            </div>
            <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q3-exp">Reveal Explanation</button>
            <div class="quiz-explanation" aria-hidden="true" id="q3-exp">
              <strong>✅ Correct Answer: A</strong><br/>
              CO₂ dissolves in water to form carbonic acid (H₂CO₃), but this reaction is reversible — the CO₂ can be exhaled as a gas. This makes it a <em>volatile</em> acid — it can be eliminated by the lungs. Lactic acid, phosphoric acid, and beta-hydroxybutyric acid are all <em>fixed</em> (non-volatile) acids that require renal excretion.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="quiz-item" data-correct="d">
            <p class="quiz-question">4. A patient on a diuretic develops pH 7.51, PaCO₂ 46, HCO₃⁻ 36. What is the likely mechanism?</p>
            <div class="quiz-options">
              <label><input type="radio" name="q4" value="a"/> The diuretic is causing hyperventilation, blowing off CO₂.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q4" value="b"/> The kidneys are generating excess CO₂ to compensate.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q4" value="c"/> Diarrhea has caused bicarbonate loss, leading to alkalosis.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q4" value="d"/> Loop/thiazide diuretics cause chloride and potassium loss, leading to contraction alkalosis and increased HCO₃⁻ reabsorption.</label>
            </div>
            <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q4-exp">Reveal Explanation</button>
            <div class="quiz-explanation" aria-hidden="true" id="q4-exp">
              <strong>✅ Correct Answer: D</strong><br/>
              Loop and thiazide diuretics cause loss of Na⁺, Cl⁻, and K⁺. Volume contraction triggers aldosterone, which promotes H⁺ excretion and HCO₃⁻ reabsorption. Hypokalemia also worsens alkalosis (K⁺ exits cells, H⁺ enters to maintain electroneutrality). This is "contraction alkalosis" — a metabolic alkalosis.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="quiz-item" data-correct="b">
            <p class="quiz-question">5. Why is CNS depression particularly severe in respiratory acidosis compared with metabolic acidosis of similar pH?</p>
            <div class="quiz-options">
              <label><input type="radio" name="q5" value="a"/> Metabolic acidosis causes more vasodilation in the brain.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q5" value="b"/> CO₂ is lipid-soluble and crosses the blood-brain barrier rapidly, directly acidifying the CSF and suppressing neurons.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q5" value="c"/> Respiratory acidosis always has a lower pH than metabolic acidosis.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q5" value="d"/> The kidneys compensate faster in metabolic acidosis, protecting the brain.</label>
            </div>
            <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q5-exp">Reveal Explanation</button>
            <div class="quiz-explanation" aria-hidden="true" id="q5-exp">
              <strong>✅ Correct Answer: B</strong><br/>
              CO₂ is a small, lipid-soluble molecule that diffuses freely across the blood-brain barrier and into cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). Once in the CSF, it converts to H⁺ which directly inhibits neuronal activity. Fixed acids from metabolic acidosis are larger, charged molecules that cross the BBB slowly, so CNS effects are more delayed. This is why CO₂ narcosis can occur rapidly.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="quiz-item" data-correct="c">
            <p class="quiz-question">6. A patient with severe diarrhea for 3 days has pH 7.28, PaCO₂ 28, HCO₃⁻ 12. The respiratory rate is 28/min. What is happening physiologically?</p>
            <div class="quiz-options">
              <label><input type="radio" name="q6" value="a"/> Respiratory alkalosis is the primary problem; kidneys are compensating.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q6" value="b"/> The low CO₂ is causing the acidosis.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q6" value="c"/> Metabolic acidosis from HCO₃⁻ loss; lungs are hyperventilating to reduce CO₂ and compensate.</label>
              <label><input type="radio" name="q6" value="d"/> This ABG is fully compensated — pH is within normal range.</label>
            </div>
            <button class="reveal-btn" aria-expanded="false" data-target="q6-exp">Reveal Explanation</button>
            <div class="quiz-explanation" aria-hidden="true" id="q6-exp">
              <strong>✅ Correct Answer: C</strong><br/>
              Diarrhea causes loss of HCO₃⁻ (intestinal/pancreatic secretions are bicarbonate-rich). HCO₃⁻ 12 is critically low → pH falls (metabolic acidosis). The lungs respond by hyperventilating (RR 28) to blow off CO₂, reducing the volatile acid component to partially compensate. pH 7.28 is still acidotic — partial compensation only. The kidneys need time to regenerate HCO₃⁻.
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

